<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-129-018 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 903 306</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  June 17 1991* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Australia: Telecom to lose many first-phone renters.andO;(demonopolization)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Zucker, Paul.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Telecom Australia (Marketing).andO;Topic:     Communications Service SuppliersStrategic PlanningTelephonesAustraliaTelephone companiesMonopoliesDeregulation.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>AUSTRALIA: TELECOM TO LOSE MANY FIRST-PHONE RENTERS 06/17/91 SYDNEY,AUSTRALIA, 1991 JUN 17 (NB) -- Telecom, Australia's communications carrier,is to offer alternate deals to phone users following the next step in phonedemonopolization.andP;  Starting July 1, Telecom's monopoly will cease, and withit will go the mandatory user rental of a supplied telephone set.andM;Telecom hopes it can hold 100 percent of first-phone renters, but observerssay users will soon realize the economies of third-party phones.andP;  To counterthis, Telecom will offer three alternatives: a continuation of the fullrental system, a 'return to base' system where the phone set won't beserviced on site, and a third option is for the customer to buy a phone fromTelecom - outright.andP;  These phones will have a warranty period, after whichusers must pay for service.andM;As most business users now use third party phones, it is hard to see howTelecom will hold onto its 'sure money' situation.andP;  Annual fees for a fullphone are $30, with $15 for the back-to-base rental.andM;(Paul Zucker/19910617)</TEXT></DOC>